SENATE BILL DRS15186-MQ-15
Short Title: Agency Vacant Property. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Burgin and Chaudhuri (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REQUIRE THE DEPARTMENT OF ADMINISTRATION TO ASSESS,
3 CATALOG, REPORT, AND DISPOSE OF CERTAIN VACANT STATE PROPERTY.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 143-341 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 143-341. Powers and duties of Department.
7 The Department of Administration has the following powers and duties:
8 (1) Repealed by Session Laws 1979, 2nd Session, c. 1137, s. 38.
9 (2) Purchase and Contract:
10 a. To exercise those powers and perform those duties which were, at the
11 time of the ratification of this Article, conferred by statute upon the
12 former Division of Purchase and Contract.
13 …
14 (4) Real Property Control:
15 a. To prepare and keep current a complete and accurate inventory of all
16 land owned or leased by the State or by any State agency. This
17 inventory shall show the location, including the latitude and longitude
18 of the center of the property, acreage, description, source of title and
19 current use of all land (including swamplands or marshlands) owned
20 by the State or by any State agency, and the agency to which each tract
21 is currently allocated. Surveys may be made where necessary to obtain
22 information for the purposes of this inventory. Accurate plats or maps
23 of all such land may be prepared, or copies obtained where such maps
24 or plats are available.
25 b. To prepare and keep current a complete and accurate database of all
26 buildings owned or leased (in whole or in part) by the State or by any
27 State agency. This database shall serve as the State inventory and shall
28 include all of the following information and floor plans of every such
29 building shall be prepared or copies obtained where such floor plans
30 are available, where needed for use in the allocation of space therein:
31 1. The building's location, including the latitude and longitude of
32 the center of the building.
33 2. A description of the operations supported by the building.
34 3. The agency or agencies that occupy the building.The current
35 occupant of the building or, if the building is vacant, the current
36 period of vacancy.
*DRS15186-MQ-15*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 4. Ownership information for the building.
2 5. The size of the building in terms of both gross and usable
3 square feet.
4 6. A description of the building.
5 7. The building's condition assessment, including the estimated
6 cost to make needed repairs and renovations as well as the date
7 that the last condition assessment was completed.
8 8. The building's annual operating costs.
9 9. The building's annual maintenance costs.
10 9a. The total potential liability to the State for the building and the
11 land where the building is situated.
12 10. The number of usable workspaces contained in the building.
13 11. The number of full-time equivalent positions assigned to the
14 building by each agency occupant.
15 12. The amount of the building that is utilized, measured in
16 accordance with the procedures developed pursuant to
17 G.S. 143-341.2(a)(3).
18 13. Maintenance record, including replacement and maintenance
19 schedules for all major mechanical systems.
20 14. Parking and employee facilities.
21 15. Any other information deemed relevant by the Department of
22 Administration.
23 …."
24 SECTION 2. G.S. 143-341.2 reads as rewritten:
25 "§ 143-341.2. Proactive management of State-owned and State-leased real property
26 portfolio.
27 (a) Duties of the Department of Administration. – The Department of Administration
28 shall have the following powers and duties:
29 (1) Development of comprehensive State facilities plan. – No later than April 1,
30 2023, and every five years thereafter, the Department of Administration shall
31 develop and implement a plan to comprehensively manage, acquire, and
32 dispose of the facilities and spaces required to fully support State government
33 operations. The plan shall do all of the following:
34 a. Identify the type, quantity, and location of facilities and spaces
35 required to fully support State government operations.
36 b. Include an in-depth analysis of existing State-owned facilities'
37 locations, capability, utilization, occupancy status, and condition.
38 c. Establish strategic priorities and objectives that allow the Department
39 of Administration to manage the performance of the State's portfolio
40 of real property in a way that maximizes the utilization of State-owned
41 facilities and minimizes operating and maintenance costs.
42 d. Take into consideration the information provided to the Department in
43 five-year real property management plans submitted by State agencies
44 pursuant to subdivision (b)(4) of this section.
45 e. Provide a mechanism for allocating available facilities or space to
46 State agencies that need it in a manner that reduces the need to acquire
47 new space through purchase, lease, or other means.
48 f. Provide recommendations for disposing of existing State property and
49 facilities, consolidating operations among existing facilities, and
50 relocating State agencies from leased facilities to State-owned
51 facilities.
Page 2 DRS15186-MQ-15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 g. Describe all changes made to space planning standards developed and
2 distributed as provided in subdivision (4) of this subsection.
3 h. Identify potential facilities eligible for surplus disposal under
4 G.S. 143-341.3.
5 (2) Development of performance management system. – The Department of
6 Administration shall establish a performance management system to measure
7 the State's achievement of the priorities and objectives set forth in plans
8 developed pursuant to subdivision (1) of this section. The system shall set
9 measurable goals and deadlines and shall be designed to focus on optimization
10 and efficiency of the State's portfolio of real property. The system shall be
11 used to report the information required by sub-sub-subdivision (7)c.1. of this
12 section.
13 (3) Development of utilization measures. – The Department of Administration
14 shall develop and distribute to State agencies procedures to be used to measure
15 the utilization of State-owned and State-leased real property. The procedures
16 developed pursuant to this subdivision shall be all of the following:
17 a. Based on the percentage of usable square feet in a facility that is used
18 for State agency functions or for storage, or on other trade industry
19 standards of utilization measurement.
20 b. Adjusted as appropriate for each facility type.
21 c. Designed to yield an easily understandable index or ratio of facility
22 utilization.
23 d. Developed in consultation with State agencies.
24 (4) Development and enforcement of space planning standards. – The Department
25 of Administration shall develop and distribute to State agencies space
26 planning standards to be used to determine workspace size and to govern the
27 use of shared space. The standards developed pursuant to this subdivision
28 shall be based on the Federal GSA's Office of Real Property Management
29 Performance Measurement Division Workspace Utilization and Allocation
30 Benchmark report unless the Department identifies another efficient industry
31 standard upon which to base the space planning standards developed pursuant
32 to this subdivision. The Department shall:
33 a. Annually perform audits of a portion of State agencies to determine
34 each agency's adherence to the space planning standards developed
35 pursuant to this subdivision and shall send formal letters of
36 admonishment to any agency that fails to justify, in the sole discretion
37 of the Department, any deviation from those standards.
38 b. Update the space planning standards developed pursuant to this
39 subdivision at least once every five years and distribute those changes
40 to State agencies.
41 (5) Updating of real property inventories. – The Department of Administration
42 shall do all of the following to ensure that the information contained in the
43 inventories maintained pursuant to G.S. 143-341(4) is kept current:
44 a. Immediately incorporate information received from State agencies
45 pursuant to subdivision (b)(1) of this section into the inventories.
46 b. Immediately notify State agencies when the incorporation of
47 information into the inventories required by sub-subdivision a. of this
48 subdivision is complete.
49 (6) Development of surplus property identification and disposal system. – The
50 Department of Administration shall establish a surplus real property disposal
51 system that limits the duration that unneeded property is retained by the State.
DRS15186-MQ-15 Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 As part of the system, the Department shall adopt rules defining surplus
2 State-owned real property and establishing a system for continuously
3 identifying and disposing of that property, subject to the approvals required
4 by Chapter 146 of the General Statutes, which shall take into consideration all
5 of the following:
6 a. The value each facility or parcel of land brings to the performance of
7 the mission of the State or State agency and the fulfillment of its goals
8 and objectives.
9 b. A general measure of the facility's condition calculated as a ratio of
10 repair needs to replacement value.
11 c. The degree to which the property is utilized, measured in accordance
12 with the procedures developed pursuant to subdivision (3) of this
13 subsection.
14 d. The extent to which the property meets the purpose for which it was
15 intended.
16 e. The extent to which the State or State agency is likely to need to
17 continue to provide the service or function currently provided at the
18 property.
19 f. Consideration of the best and most cost-effective manner in which
20 these future needs can be met.
21 (7) Reporting. – The Department of Administration shall make the following
22 reports:
23 a. No later than April 1, 2023, and every five years thereafter, the
24 Department shall report the following to the Joint Legislative
25 Commission on Governmental Operations and Joint Legislative
26 Oversight Committee on Capital Improvements, Joint Legislative
27 Oversight Committee on General Government, and Fiscal Research
28 Division:
29 1. The plan developed pursuant to subdivision (1) of this
30 subsection.
31 2. A summary of the performance measurement procedures
32 developed pursuant to subdivision (2) of this subsection.
33 b. If any State agency fails to submit the information required by
34 subdivision (b)(1) of this section, the Department shall report the
35 failure to the chairs of the Joint Legislative Commission on
36 Governmental Operations, the chairs of the Joint Legislative Oversight
37 Committee on Capital Improvements, and the chairs of the Joint
38 Legislative Oversight Committee on General Government within 30
39 days.
40 c. No later than April 1, 2024, and each year thereafter, the Department
41 shall report to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental
42 Operations, Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Capital
43 Improvements, Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on General
44 Government, and Fiscal Research Division on the State's portfolio of
45 real property. This report shall include at least the following
46 information:
47 1. The status of achieving the goals and objectives set forth in the
48 most recent plan developed pursuant to subdivision (1) of this
49 section.
Page 4 DRS15186-MQ-15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 2. Trends in the inventory of leased and owned buildings and real
2 property, including changes in value, square footage, and
3 operation and maintenance costs.
4 3. Trends in the inventory of State-owned land, including
5 changes in acreage and value.
6 4. Allocation of leased and owned space by facility type, by
7 agency, and by county.
8 5. Benchmarks for comparable private sector leases across the
9 regions of the State for both rural and urban locations, as
10 appropriate.
11 6. An analysis of utilization targets and a list of owned and leased
12 real property identified as unused or underutilized.
13 7. A list of the following information for the period beginning
14 after submission of the most recent report pursuant to this
15 sub-subdivision:
16 I. State-owned properties identified as unused or
17 underutilized.
18 II. State-owned properties sold.
19 III. State-owned properties in the process of being disposed
20 of.
21 IV. Properties reallocated between State agencies.
22 8. A list of all audits performed that year pursuant to
23 sub-subdivision a. of subdivision (4) of this subsection, a
24 summary of the findings of each audit, and the agency's plans
25 for addressing the findings of the audit.
26 (b) Duties of Other State Agencies. – Each State agency shall have the following powers
27 and duties:
28 (1) Collection and reporting of information on property use. – No later than
29 November 1, 2022, and each year thereafter, each State agency shall submit
30 to the Department of Administration all of the information described in
31 G.S. 143-341(4)b.1. through 15. for each building, facility, or space in any
32 building or facility that the agency occupies. This shall be in addition to any
33 reports required pursuant to G.S. 143-341(4)h.
34 (2) Verification of information in real property inventories. – Within 60 days of
35 receiving notice from the Department of Administration pursuant to
36 sub-subdivision (a)(5)b. of this section, each State agency shall report to the
37 Department one of the following, as applicable:
38 a. That the information submitted to the Department of Administration
39 pursuant to subdivision (1) of this subsection is accurately reflected in
40 the real property inventories.
41 b. A list of discrepancies between the information submitted to the
42 Department of Administration pursuant to subdivision (1) of this
43 subsection and the corresponding information in the real property
44 inventories.
45 (3) Auditor may audit submissions. – The State Auditor may audit submissions
46 made to the Department of Administration pursuant to subdivision (1) of this
47 subsection and may recover any costs incurred in performing such an audit
48 from the State Land Fund, in accordance with G.S. 146-72.
49 (4) Development of five-year property management plan. – No later than
50 November 1, 2022, and every five years thereafter, each State agency shall
51 develop a five-year real property management plan and shall submit the plan
DRS15186-MQ-15 Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to the Department of Administration for review. Each plan shall do all of the
2 following:
3 a. Identify the type, quantity, and location of facilities and spaces
4 required to fully support agency operations.
5 b. Include an in-depth analysis of existing facilities' locations,
6 capabilities, utilization, and condition.
7 c. Establish agency-specific strategic priorities and objectives for each
8 asset under its control.
9 (c) Exception for Property Not Subject to Department of Administration Oversight. –
10 None of the requirements of this section shall apply to facilities that are not subject to the real
11 property oversight of the Department of Administration under G.S. 143-341. A State agency that
12 is entirely exempt from the real property oversight of the Department of Administration shall not
13 be required to submit any information pursuant to subsection (b) of this section. A State agency
14 that is partially exempt from the real property oversight of the Department of Administration
15 shall submit information pursuant to subsection (b) of this section for those properties that are
16 subject to the real property oversight of the Department of Administration."
17 SECTION 3. Part 1 of Article 36 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes is amended
18 by adding a new section to read:
19 "§ 143-341.3. Disposal of surplus real property.
20 (a) Surplus Real Property Disposal. – The Department of Administration shall establish
21 a surplus real property disposal system that limits the duration that unneeded or vacant property
22 is retained by the State. As part of the system, the Department shall (i) adopt rules in accordance
23 with this section, including defining surplus State-owned real property, and (ii) establish a system
24 for continuously identifying and disposing of that property, subject to the approvals required
25 under Chapter 146 of the General Statutes, which shall take into consideration all of the
26 following:
27 (1) The value each facility or parcel of land brings to the performance of the
28 mission of the State or State agency and the fulfillment of its goals and
29 objectives.
30 (2) A general measure of the facility's condition calculated as a ratio of repair
31 needs to replacement value.
32 (3) The degree to which the property is utilized, measured in accordance with the
33 procedures developed pursuant to G.S. 143-341.2(a)(3).
34 (4) The extent to which the property meets the purpose for which it was intended.
35 (5) The extent to which the State or State agency is likely to need to continue to
36 provide the service or function currently provided at the property.
37 (6) Consideration of the best and most cost-effective manner in which these future
38 needs can be met.
39 (7) Whether the property has been vacant for one year or longer.
40 (8) An assessment of private or public interest in the property.
41 (b) Method for Disposal. – For properties identified as surplus pursuant to this section,
42 the Department of Administration shall, subject to the approvals required under Chapter 146 of
43 the General Statutes, dispose of the surplus real property by sale. If the Department of
44 Administration is unable to dispose of the real property by sale for a period of six months, the
45 Department shall dispose of the property by auction or by transfer of title to a city or county in
46 this State, provided that the city or county presents evidence satisfactory to the Department of an
47 economic development use for the property.
48 (c) Proceeds of Sale. – Notwithstanding G.S. 146-15, G.S. 146-30, or any other provision
49 of law, the gross proceeds of the sale of surplus real property under this section shall be handled
50 in accordance with the following priority:
Page 6 DRS15186-MQ-15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) First, by subtracting any expenses incurred incident to the sale as may be
2 allowed under rules and regulations adopted by the Governor and approved
3 by the Council of State.
4 (2) Second, in accordance with the provisions of any trust or other instrument of
5 title whereby title to real property was acquired.
6 (3) Third, as provided by any other act of the General Assembly.
7 (4) Fourth, by depositing the remaining proceeds in accordance with the
8 following:
9 a. Fifty percent (50%) to the General Fund.
10 b. Fifty percent (50%) to the Department of Administration to be used
11 for repair and renovation projects as provided in G.S. 143C-8-13."
12 SECTION 4. No later than three months after the effective date of this section, the
13 Department of Administration shall submit a report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee
14 on General Government and the Fiscal Research Division with the vacant building data required
15 under G.S. 143-341, as enacted in this act.
16 SECTION 5. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025.
